// tests/snippets/int_width_union_is — `is` on a union mixing integer
// widths narrows incorrectly, and the two backends disagree.
//
// Repro of a VM/native divergence found 2026-07-16 by differential fuzzing
// (VM vs native C-emit). PARKED (2026-07-16): deprioritized behind
// narrow_int_wrap; kept as a record. This is the integer analog of the
// f32-union `is` fix (e29891685).
//
// For `x: i32 | i64 | u8`, `tag` should report 1 for a u8, 2 for an i64, 3 for
// a free-i32-literal — i.e. `1 2 3`.
//
//   backend   output   what happens
//   expected  1 2 3    each width distinguished
//   VM        1 1 1    the FIRST `is <intType>` tested matches ANY integer
//                      value (coarse I64 box tag matches every width)
//   native    3 2 3    `is i64` works, but `is u8` NEVER matches a real u8
//                      (a u8 value is boxed with a tag != the u8 type-id)
//
// Neither backend is correct AND they diverge. Design question (open): reject
// width-mixed integer unions at the typer, alias all widths for `is` (as
// f32 was aliased to f64), or carry precise primitive tags in the box.

module "snippet"

import "std/io"

tag :: fn(x: i32 | i64 | u8) -> i32 {
    if x is u8  { return 1 }
    if x is i64 { return 2 }
    return 3
}

main :: fn() -> i32 {
    a: u8 = 5
    b: i64 = 9999999999
    // expected "1 2 3" ; VM prints "1 1 1" ; native prints "3 2 3"
    println("${tag(a)} ${tag(b)} ${tag(7)}")
    return 0
}
